2. Cardona's return to Monterrey's starting XI ends badly 
 
Monterrey coach Antonio Mohamed handed Colombian international Edwin Cardona his first Liga MX start in five months and it ended with a red card in the 22nd minute. 
 
The debate raged over whether Cardona raised his arm with intentional force to strike Leon's Fernando Navarro, but the 24-year-old gave the referee a decision to make when he didn't really need to. 
 
The player asked for forgiveness from the fans after the game, but it was the latest chapter in a strange relationship between Cardona -- one paper on of the best players in Liga MX -- and Monterrey. It just doesn't seem to be working and watching it is highly frustrating. 
 
Rayados managed to scrape a 0-0 draw against Leon, but Mohamed is still scrambling to put together a side that works as well on the pitch as it looks on paper. 
   
3. Pressure on Cruz Azul's Jemez as Xolos stay top 
 
Miguel Herrera's Club Tijuana remains top of the Liga MX after racking up its second consecutive 1-0 victory, this time at Estadio Caliente against Cruz Azul on Friday. 
 
A set piece goal from Juan Carlos Valenzuela was enough to take the points in a bitterly fought game with a total of 38 fouls over the 90 minutes and in which neither team was able to really dominate. 
 
Martin Rodriguez's miss in the first half could've changed the course of the whole game, but the bottom line now is that La Maquina is without a win in five. 
 
"Football is punishing us," said Spanish coach Paco Jemez after the match, adding that the result was unfair and that no fan could criticize the effort and performance his team put on. 
 
Jemez's take is a perfectly rational way of looking at the game and his team's lack of luck over the last two weeks; it's just that things at Cruz Azul have rarely been rational over the last few years. There will inevitably be talk about crisis and such, as unfair as that will seem to Jemez. 
 
